.pl 62
                            Chapter 1


                    Introduction and Overview


1.1 INTRODUCTION

The  DSI-32  Assembler  enables  the  user  to  assemble  NS32000 
assembly  language statements.  The Assembler produces an  object 
file  that may then be linked by the DSI-32 Linker to produce  an 
executable program.  It is recommended that the user have a  copy 
of  the  National  Semiconductor Instruction Set manual  for  the 
32000 series of microprocessors. (Order from Definicon Systems or 
National Semiconductors: Document NSP-INST-REF-M).

The   manual  contains  a  detailed  description  of  the  DSI-32 
Assembler  language.  The  various chapters  that  comprise  this 
manual contain the following information:

   - Chapter  1,  Introduction and Overview.  Introduces the DSI-
     32 and lists its features.

   - Chapter  2,  DSI-32 Language Elements.  Defines the form  of 
     DSI-32 Assembler statements,  constants,  terms, symbols and 
     expression syntax.

   - Chapter  3,  DSI-32  Programs.  Describes  the  support  for 
     modules,  segments,  relocation modes,  the various location 
     counters and the various assembly modes.
	
   - Chapter  4,  Instruction  Operands.  The  syntax  of  DSI-32 
     operands is described.

   - Chapter 5,  DSI-32 Assembler Pseudo-Operands.  The syntax of 
     the DSI-32 pseudo-ops is described.

   - Chapter 6, Procedures. Defines the format of a procedure and 
     the syntax of procedure control pseudo-ops.

   - Chapter  7,  Invocation and Operation.  The operation of the 
     Assembly is described as well as options and error messages.

   - Appendix  A,  Reserved Symbols.  The DSI-32 reserved symbols 
     are defined.
.pa
1.2  OVERVIEW OF THE DSI-32 ASSEMBLER

The  DSI-32  Assembler provides a variety of features  which  aid 
assembly language programming.

 - Assembler Input  and  Output  Files.
An object code file and an optional listing file are produced  by 
the  DSI-32  Assembler.  The object code file once linked by  the 
DSI-32  Linker forms an executable file which may then be  loaded 
by  the  Definicon  Systems' LOAD program.  The listing  file  is 
formed  from  the assembled code,  the source  line  number,  the 
source statements and any error messages. Input and Output files, 
listing file format,  and error messages are described in Chapter 
7.
 - Instruction  Set.
The  complete NS32032 instruction set is supported by the  DSI-32 
Assembler.    All   the  memory-management   and   floating-point 
instructions are also supported by the Assembler.

 - Addressing  Modes.
The Assembler supports the nine general addressing modes:

  (1)  register
  (2)  register relative
  (3)  memory
  (4)  immediate
  (5)  absolute
  (6)  top of stack
  (7)  external
  (8)  memory relative
  (9)  scaled index

 - Data  Types.
The  Assembler supports the following data  types:  byte,  signed 
byte,  word,  signed  word and  double-word,  signed  double-word 
integers  single  and  double-precision  floating-point  numbers, 
packed decimal numbers, bits, and bit fields.

 - Assembler Pseudo Opcodes.
The Assembler provides a variety of pseudo-ops to define symbols, 
allocate  storage,  allocate  constants,  manage  procedures  and 
control program segments.

 - Procedures.
A  special  set of pseudo-ops,  called the  procedure  management 
pseudo-ops,  are  supported by the assembler to make the creation 
of  program  procedures  simple.   These  pseudo-ops  enable  the 
programmer  to  write modular routines that may recursively  call 
themselves.  The pseudo-ops create a frame on stack for temporary 
data  storage  of  the  parameters,   return  values,  and  local 
variables of the procedure.
1.3  NS32000 REGISTERS

The  NS32000 system consists of four sets of register types which 
are detailed below:

  - General-Purpose registers (on the CPU)
  - Dedicated registers (on the CPU)
  - Floating-Point registers (on the FPU)
  - Memory-Management registers (on the MMU)


1.3.1  General-Purpose Registers

The eight General-Purpose registers are:  R0, R1, R2, R3, R4, R5, 
R6 and R7.

Each  general purpose register is 32 bits long and may be used in 
byte,  word,  and  double word operations.  Only the bits in  the 
length specified by the instruction type are affected.

General  purpose  registers  may  be combined  to  form  even/odd 
register pairs as follows:   R0/R1,  R2/R3,  R4/R5, R6/R7. The 64 
bit  register  pairs  are used  by  various  extended  arithmetic 
instructions which produce a 64 bit result.  Register pair  names 
are: R0, R2, R4, and R6.

.pa
1.3.2  Dedicated Registers

The   eight  dedicated  registers  contain  pointers  to   memory 
locations and status information.

 Register                Name      Contents
 --------                ----      --------

 Program Counter          PC       pointer to current instruction
 Interrupt Stack Pointer  SP0      pointer to top Interrupt Stack
 User Stack Pointer       SP1      pointer to top of User Stack
 Frame Pointer            FP       pointer to current Frame
 Static Base              SB       pointer to current Static Base 
                                   Area
 Interrupt Base           INTBASE  pointer  to Exception Dispatch 
                                   Table
 Module                   MOD      pointer   to  current   Module 
                                   Descriptor
 Processor Status         PSR      processor status flags

The  PC, SP0, SP1, FP, SB and INTBASE registers are 32 bits long. 
However, since these registers contain memory addresses, and only 
the  low-order  24 bits are used in the NS32032 the high-order  8 
bits are zeroed by the processor, the assembler treats them as 32 
bit registers.  The MOD and PSR registers are 16 bits  long.  The 
MOD  register  contains a memory pointer,  and the  PSR  register 
contains  the  processor  status flags.  Even  though  two  stack 
pointers have been described a program uses only one of the stack 
registers  at any given time.  The particular register in use  is 
determined by the context of the processor.

The  CPU selects SP0 as the current stack pointer if the 'S'  bit 
in the PSR is 0, and SP1 if the 'S' bit is 1. This enables 'user' 
and 'supervisor' stacks to be separated.

The  currently selected stack is referenced via the SP symbol.  A 
program may only change which stack will be accessed, by changing 
the  'S' bit.  The Assembler does  not,  therefore,  support  the 
symbols SP0 and SP1. 

The  PSR  status  flags  define the current CPU  status  and  the 
results  of  previous instruction(s).  The layout of the  PSR  is 
shown below:
.pa
      Supervisor Flags                   User Flags
+-------------------------------+-------------------------------+
| x   x   x   x | I | P | S | U | N | Z | F | x   x | L | T | C |
+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+
15                                                              0
x - reserved

The status flags have the following functions:

  User Flags (available in both user and supervisor modes)
  ----------

  C       is  the carry flag.  The 'C' bit indicates a  carry  or 
          borrow   occurred  after  an  addition  or  subtraction 
          instruction. 'C' is used in the calculation of multiple 
          precision arithmetic.  A value of '1' means a carry  or 
          borrow, a value of '0' means no carry or borrow.

  T       is  the  Trace Trap flag.  The 'T' bit enables  program 
          tracing.  If  this bit is a '1' a TRC trap is  executed 
          after each instruction.  See also 'P' flag.

  L       is  the  Low flag.  The 'L' bit is  set  by  comparison 
          instructions.   In a comparison instruction the 'L' bit 
          is  set to '1' if the second  operand is less than  the 
          first,  when  both operands are interpreted as unsigned 
          integers, otherwise it is set to '0'.

  F       is the General Condition flag. The 'F' bit is a general 
          flag which is used by many instructions. 

  Z       is  the Zero flag.   The 'Z' flag is set by  comparison 
          instructions.   In a comparison instruction the 'Z' bit 
          is  set to a '1' if the second operand is equal to  the 
          first operand, otherwise it is set to '0'.

  N       is the Negative flag. The 'N' flag is set by comparison 
          instructions.   In a comparison instruction the 'N' bit 
          is  set  to '1' if the second operand is less than  the 
          first  operand,  when both operands are interpreted  as 
          signed integers, otherwise it is set to '0'.

  Supervisor Flags (available to supervisor program only)
  ----------------

  U       is  the  user Mode flag.  The User Mode flag  sets  the 
          current mode of system operation.  If 'U' bit is set to 
          '1'   no  privileged  instructions  may   be   executed 
          otherwise            if 'U' is 0,  the system is in the 
          supervisor mode and all instructions may be executed.
.pa
  S       is  the Stack flag.  The 'S' bit specifies whether  the 
          SP0  or  the SP1 register is to be used  as  the  stack 
          pointer.  The  'S'  bit  is  automatically  cleared  on 
          interrupts  and  traps.  It may have a setting  of  '0' 
          (SP0) or '1' (SP1).

  P       is  the Trace Pending flag.  The 'P' bit prevents a TRC 
          trap from occurring more than once for an  instruction. 
          The 'T' flag contents are copied to the 'P' flag at the 
          start of an instruction. At the end of the instruction, 
          if  P is 1,  a trace trap is taken otherwise if P is 0, 
          no trace trap is taken.  The 'P' flag is cleared when a 
          trace  is  taken to prevent a second  trace  trap  from 
          occurring.

  I       is the Interrupt flag. Interrupts are enabled If 'I' is 
          '1' otherwise if 'I' is '0', then all interrupts except 
          the Non-Maskable Interrupt are disabled.

.pa
1.3.3  Floating-Point Registers

The  Floating-Point  registers are primarily intended to  provide 
fast  temporary  storage  for  floating  point  operations.   The 
eight floating point registers are:  F0,  F1,  F2, F3, F4, F5, F6 
and  F7.   The  registers are 32 bits long and may  hold  single-
precision ieee floating-point numbers.

The  Floating-Point  registers  may be combined to  form  64  bit 
even/odd register pairs: F0/F1, F2/F3, F4/F5, F6/F7.  Each of the 
register  pairs may hold a double-precision  ieee  floating-point 
number.  The high order part of the floating point number is held 
in  the   odd  register and the low order part  is  in  the  even 
register.  Register pair names are: F0, F2, F4, and F6.

The  Floating-Point  Status Register (FSR) describes the  current 
mode of the FPU as well as any error status due to the  execution 
of the last floating point instruction.


1.3.4  Memory-Management Registers

The  Memory  Management  registers  enable  the  various  options 
available  in  the  MMU to be manipulated.  The  various  Memory-
Management registers are described below.  All  Memory-Management 
registers, except SC0 and SC1, are 32 bits long.  The SC0 and SC1 
logical  registers are 16 bits long and occupy a single  physical 
32 bit register within the MMU.

Register                     Name       Function
--------                     ----       --------

Page  Table  Register  0     PTB0       Specifies  the current
                                        base address of the Level
                                        1 Page Table.

Page Table Register 1        PTB1       Specifies the current
                                        base address of the  user
                                        mode Level  1 Page Table.

Error/Invalidate Address     EIA        When an error  occurs, it
                                        contains   the    virtual
                                        address that  caused  the
                                        exception to occur.  When 
                                        the register  is  written
                                        to it informs the MMU  to
                                        remove the entry from the 
                                        cache in the MMU.
.pa
Breakpoint  Register  0      BPR0       Specifies  the address at
                                        which a  breakpoint is to
                                        occur. 

Breakpoint Register 1        BPR1       Specifies the  address at 
                                        which a breakpoint  is to  
                                        occur.

Breakpoint Count             BCNT       Specifies the  number  of
                                        breakpoints   that   have
                                        occurred      at      the  
                                        BPR0

                                        address.  Once the  count
                                        reached zero then a break 
                                        will be generated.

Program Flow 0               PF0        Contains  the address  of 
                                        the  previous  nonsequen-
                                        tial instruction.

Program Flow 1               PF1        Contains  the address  of 
                                        the   last  nonsequential 
                                        instruction.

Sequential Count 0           SC0        The count of instructions
                                        executed  since the  last 
                                        nonsequential instruction
Sequential Count 1           SC1        The count  of  sequential 
                                        instructions     executed 
                                        prior  to   the last non-
                                        sequential instruction

Memory Status Register       MSR        Contains  the status  and 
                                        mode of the MMU.

.pa
1.4  DOCUMENTATION CONVENTIONS

The  following documentation conventions are used  in  describing 
the DSI-32 Assembler.

          Upper-case  letters show the instruction and pseudo  op 
          mnemonics.   The  mnemonics must be entered exactly  as 
          shown.

          Spaces or blanks,  when present,  are significant; they 
          must   be  entered  as  shown.    Multiple  blanks   or 
          horizontal tabs may be used in place of a single blank.

     <> - angle  brackets  enclose  descriptive names  (in  lower 
          case) for user-supplied operands.

     {} - braces enclose two or more items of which one, and only 
          one,  must be used.   The items are separated from each 
          other by a logical OR sign "|".

     [] - brackets enclose optional item(s).

      | - logical OR sign separates items of which one,  and only 
          one, may be used.

    ... - three consecutive periods indicate optional  repetition 
          of the preceding item.

    ,,, - three  consecutive commas indicate optional  repetition 
          of  the  preceding item.   Items must be  separated  by 
          commas.

